kanji.Meaning: both; counter for carriages/cars (e.g./ in a train)

両方 (りょうほう) both; both sides

kanji.Koohii1: Primatives celing; belt; mountain as per Cumulative Errata. See volfy post for link. Both effective ways to commit suicide/ hang your self from the celing with your belt or jump off a mountain.
kanji.Koohii2: Both of Tiger Wood´s initials is the logo on his belt...

kanji.Koohii2: Your halberd doesn´t have a handguard? You should have thought of that beforehand (i.e./ before you were missing your hand).

kanji.Koohii1: This can be seen as a Retarius/ a roman gladiator. The Retiarius always fought with a net to bound up his opponents/ and with a trident/ which was able to pierce enemies after tying them. They were terrific contenders/ so they were only paired with gladiators specially equipped to fight them.
kanji.Koohii2: A boxing ring is bound up by the ropes. The contender is cheating and using a rake.

kanji.Koohii1: Even though your FATHER is an old man/ he can´t give up his party lifestyle. Once a week he still dons his cool TOP HAT (well/ it was cool 40 years ago) and goes out on the town to MINGLE with the ladies. This is a pretty common thing in Japan/ where old motherfuckers still think they can pick up 19 year old girls.
kanji.Koohii2: Darth Vader tries to mingle with his troops. He even weares one of the helmets of the stromtroopers. (one of them laughs: white helmet/ black suit. Darth Vader thereby slashes him in 2).

kanji.Koohii2: It´s one or the other: fight Mr. T/ or be thrown into the scorpion pit.

grammar.Meaning: try to; attempt to; be about to ~

sentences.sentence_japanese: その会社は、他社との外交関係を改善しようとしている。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: The company is trying to improve its diplomatic relations with other companies.

sentences.sentence_japanese: 彼は、古い車を新しい車に交換しようとした。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: He tried to exchange his old car for a new one.

sentences.sentence_japanese: 政府は、交通事故を予防しようとしている。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: The government is trying to prevent traffic accidents.

sentences.sentence_japanese: 彼女は、天気予報を予測しようとした。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: She tried to predict the weather forecast.

sentences.sentence_japanese: 彼らは、プロジェクトの予算を下げようとした。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: They tried to lower the budget for the project.

grammar.Grammar: を通じて / を通して（をつうじて / をとおして）

grammar_sentences.grammar_point: をを通じて / を通して（をつうじて / をとおして）

sentences.sentence_japanese: 外交を通じて、私たちは他の国々との強い関係を築くことができる。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: Through diplomacy, we can build strong relationships with other countries.

sentences.sentence_japanese: 他社との情報交換を通じて、私たちは交通安全の重要性を学んだ。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: We learned about the importance of traffic safety through the exchange of information with other companies.

sentences.sentence_japanese: 予報を通じて、台風が私たちの地域を通過すると予測された。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: The weather forecast predicted that the typhoon would pass through our region.

sentences.sentence_japanese: 予約制のレストランは、ウェブサイトを通じて予約した。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: We made reservations through the website for the popular restaurant.

sentences.sentence_japanese: 予防を通じて、交通事故の数を減らすことができる。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: Through prevention, we can reduce the number of traffic accidents.

sentences.sentence_japanese: 海外に行くたびに、空港で両替をする。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: Every time I go abroad, I exchange money at the airport.

sentences.sentence_japanese: 毎月、他社との会議があるたびに、予算について話し合う。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: We have a meeting with another company every month.

sentences.sentence_japanese: 病院に行くたびに、薬の処方箋をもらう。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: Every time I go to the doctor, I get a prescription for medicine.

sentences.sentence_japanese: 旅行に行くたびに、天気予報をチェックする。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: Every time I travel, I check the weather forecast.

sentences.sentence_japanese: 新しい人と出会うたびに、何かしら学ぼうとする。
sentences.sentence_english_translation: Every time I meet a new person, I try to learn something from them.

short_text_with_quiz.text_japanese: 銀行に行って両替をしました。とても混んでいましたが、スムーズに手続きを終えることができました。来週の天気予報も確認しました。予報によると、来週は雨が降る可能性があります。あまり雨が降らないことを願っています。
short_text_with_quiz.text_english: I went to the bank to exchange some money. It was very crowded, but I was able to finish the transaction quickly. I also checked the weather forecast for next week. According to the forecast, there is a chance of rain next week. I hope it won't rain too much.

reading_comprehension_quiz_in_japanese.question: 来週の天気について、何がわかりますか？

options.text: 来週の天気予報では、雨の予報が出ています。
来週は、雨が降らない予定です。
来週の天気は、まだわかりません。

song_lyrics.lyrics_japanese:
また電車が遅れてるみたい。
別に予定があるわけじゃないから、まあいいんだけど。
待ち時間に本でも読もうかな。
ゆっくりでいいや、急ぐ必要もないし。
ちょっと面倒だけど、
これも日常の一部だよね。
予測できないことはたくさんある。
落ち着いて、うまく乗り切ろう。
song_lyrics.lyrics_english_translation:
The train is delayed again, it seems. 
It’s not like I have an appointment, so it’s fine. 
I'll just read a book while I wait, 
I’ll take my time, no need to rush. 
It's a bit of a hassle though, 
But this is part of daily life, right? 
We can’t always predict what will happen. 
I’ll try to remain calm and make the best of it.

kanji_list.image_description: A vibrant, futuristic city with two sleek, silver cars zooming across a skybridge, their headlights illuminating the cityscape. Each car has a giant numeral '1' painted on its side. The skybridge is shaped like an upside-down box, and the city's buildings resemble mountains.

A whimsical clock face with a giant 'L' hand pointing to the 'before' section of the clock. The clock face is surrounded by a shimmering aura, suggesting the passage of time. A small, smiling 'I' figure stands beside the clock, looking hopeful and eager.

A chaotic scene of two cartoon pigs wearing boxing gloves and fighting in a ring made of 'wrapping' paper. The ring is surrounded by a crowd of cheering chickens, all holding 'feathered sticks' and shouting excitedly. The air is filled with sparks and smoke.

A party scene with a giant kettle lid, overflowing with colorful balloons and confetti. A cheerful 'father' figure stands at the entrance, greeting a stream of guests who are all carrying miniature kettle lids on their heads, symbolizing their coming and going. The atmosphere is celebratory and festive.

A mirrored world where every person has a twin. One person, representing 'another,' stands alone in a dark, empty space. The other, representing 'the others,' enjoys a vibrant party filled with light and laughter. The 'to be' symbol floats above the party, suggesting the presence of both worlds.
